            <term xml:id="term-k000253-1" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin-nt">jia</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000253-2" xml:lang="zh-Hant">架</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000253-3" xml:lang="zh-Hans">架</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000253-4" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin">jià</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000253-5" xml:lang="zh-latn-wadegile">chia</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000253-6" xml:lang="en" source="#biblk000253-1" >frame</term>
            <idno type="URI">https://architecturasinica.org/keyword/k000253</idno>
            <note type="Note">
               <p>Under construction</p>
               <p xml:lan="en">In Chinese traditional architecture, jia 架 serves as a technical term for measuring the depth of buildings, commonly expressed in phrases like “three bays and five jia” 
                  (san jian wu jia 三間五架) (Ouyang and Song, 1975, p. 532). However, the specific meaning of “jia” underwent a significant transformation during the <term ref="/keyword/k000082">Tang</term> dynasty.</p>
               <p xml:lan="en">The term jia first appeared in <term ref="/keyword/k000020">Eastern Han</term> dynasty literature (Zheng and Jia, 1999, p. 237), where it referred to a structural unit in which two pillars supported one purlin. 
                  Around the Tang dynasty, its meaning shifted to denote a unit in the roof's transverse direction (<term ref="/keyword/k000255">hengjia</term> 橫架; perpendicular to the roof ridge) where two purlins (or pillars) supported 
                  one rafter, and this unit became the standard for measuring room depth.</p>
               <p xml:lan="en">The evolution in the meaning of jia as a standard measure of room depth may be related to the structural transformation of wooden buildings that occurred between the Han and 
                  Tang dynasties–specifically, the shift in the main structural framework from being aligned parallel to the primary roof ridge (longitudinal frame, zongjia 縱架) to being oriented 
                  perpendicular to the roof ridge (transverse frame, hengjia 橫架). However, the dual meanings of jia as a unit in the roof's construction and a standard for measuring room depth continued 
                  to coexist from the Tang through the <term ref="/keyword/k000070">Qing</term> dynasty. This parallel usage likely persisted because many texts, especially official regulations and codes, tended to directly inherit institutional 
                  conventions from previous dynasties without adapting to practical changes in construction methods (Jiang, Zhuge and Jia, 2024).</p>
               <p xml:lang="zh-Hant">架作為中國古建築術語是計量建築進深規模的單位，常見用法如“三間五架”。（歐陽和宋 1975，532）。但“架”具體所指，在唐代發生重要變化。架最早见於東漢文献（鄭和賈 1999，237），指两柱承一檩的结构单元；
                  大約在唐代，架出現新的意涵，指山面方向两檁（柱）承一椽的單元，並以此為單位計量房間進深。</p>
               <p xml:lang="zh-Hant">架的所指及計架視角的轉變，可能與漢代至唐代木構建築的轉型，即主體結構從平行於正脊方向轉向垂直於正脊方向的構架有關。但唐代以後直至清代，兩種計架視角仍並行。其原因可能是許多文獻，尤其是官方律令，
                  更多是在制度層面對前朝成式的直接承襲，未能回應實際情況的改變。（蔣，諸葛和賈，2024）</p>
            </note>
